The HTML code you have provided contains several typographical errors involving the use of curly quotes (‘ and ’) instead of standard straight quotes ('). This is likely the cause of the "Uncaught SyntaxError: Invalid or unexpected token" error that you're seeing in your browser. JavaScript requires standard quotes for string literals and object keys.

Here is the corrected version of your JavaScript code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>YouTube Niche Finder Tool</title>
    <style>
        /* Add your CSS styling here */
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>YouTube Niche Finder</h1>
    <input type="text" id="searchQuery" placeholder="Enter a keyword…">
    <button id="searchBtn">Find Niche</button>
    <div id="results"></div>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('searchBtn').addEventListener('click', () => {
            const query = document.getElementById('searchQuery').value;
            fetch('/search', {
                method: 'POST',
                headers: {
                    'Content-Type': 'application/json',
                },
                body: JSON.stringify({ query }), // send the search query to the server
            })
            .then(response => response.json())
            .then(data => {
                document.getElementById('results').textContent = `Competition Level: ${data.competition}`;
            })
            .catch(error => {
                console.error('Error:', error);
                document.getElementById('results').textContent = 'An error occurred.';
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

I have replaced all `‘` and `’` with standard straight quotes `'` and also corrected the HTML attributes `lang`, `charset`, `http-equiv`, `name`, and `type` by replacing curly quotes with straight quotes. Additionally, I added backticks `` ` `` around the string template literal that contains the `${data.competition}` expression in `textContent`.

Also, I've introduced error handling to the fetch request with `.catch()`, so if there is an error during the fetch operation, it will be logged to the console and a message will be displayed within the `results` div.

After you replace the HTML and JavaScript in your `index.html` file with the corrected version above, your "Find Niche" button should work as expected, sending a POST request to the '/search' route on your Flask server and displaying the result on the page.
